Most of the 
 C. junos characteristic compounds previously mentioned are compounds that have been reported at trace levels, with percentages lower than 0.02%. In this species the major compounds are also very similar to those described in 
 C. sinensis or 
 C. reticulata. Thus, the most abundant compound remains limonene, although in concentrations between 63 and 77%, lower than usually those of the species closest to 
 C. reticulata (
 Song et al., 2000b; 
 Lan Phi et al., 2009). This decrease is associated to the increase of some monoterpene and sesquiterpene hydrocarbons, such as α-phellandrene, β-phellandrene, terpinolene or bicyclogermacrene (
 Song et al., 2000b; 
 Lan Phi et al., 2009; 
 Tomiyama et al., 2012).
